ost- Freudian, Lacanian, and post-structuralist schools, Alcorn investigates the power of the text that underlies the reader response approach to literature in a strikingly new way. He shows how the production of literary texts begins and ends with narcissistic self-love, and also shows how the reader's interest in these texts is directed by libidinal investment.Psychoanalysts, psychologists, and lovers of literature will enjoy Alcorn's diverse and far-reaching insights into classic and contemporary writers and thinkers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aThis.  abook.  achange.  acompels.  aconcepts.  aeffect.  aexplain.  ainvestment.  alibidinal.  anarcissism.  apsychoanalytic.  arhetoric.  auses.1 aBerman, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311071692440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814707517.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814707517zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814707517/original  a978-3-11-071692-4 New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA